I think you’ve just hit the question underneath all the others.

Not “Why do we compress?”

But…

“Why is compression possible at all?”

I don’t know.

But I can tell you what it would imply.

⸻

Imagine a universe with no compression.

Every grain of sand behaves uniquely.

Every electron has different rules.

Every sunrise is governed by entirely new laws.

Nothing transfers.

Nothing generalizes.

Knowledge cannot accumulate.

Science is impossible.

Language is impossible.

Life probably never gets very far.

There are no “kinds” of things—only individual events.

A finite mind would drown.

⸻

Now imagine the opposite.

A universe with maximum compression.

One equation predicts everything perfectly.

No novelty.

No emergence.

No surprises.

No games.

No evolution.

No creativity.

Nothing to discover because everything is already explicit.

That’s not our universe either.

⸻

Our universe seems to sit in a remarkable middle.

It has compressibility, but not complete compressibility.

Simple rules…

…complex consequences.

⸻

Now here’s the part that I find beautiful.

Compression isn’t merely making something shorter.

It’s discovering that many apparent differences…

…are actually manifestations of one deeper invariant.

For example:

Thousands of falling objects.

↓

One law.

Or…

Thousands of spoken sentences.

↓

Finite grammar.

Or…

Millions of faces.

↓

Common developmental biology.

Compression is the discovery that variety has structure.

⸻

But your question was why.

Here’s where I stop knowing and start hypothesizing.

Hypothesis 1: Compression is a consequence of symmetry.

If reality contains repeated structures, then description can be reused.

Symmetry creates redundancy.

Redundancy enables compression.

That idea has strong support in mathematics and physics.

⸻

Hypothesis 2: Compression is a consequence of causality.

One cause generates many effects.

Knowing the cause is shorter than memorizing every effect.

The world unfolds recursively.

So the generator is smaller than its output.

Think of a tiny computer program generating a complex fractal.

⸻

Hypothesis 3: Compression is a prerequisite for observers.

This is the one I find most intriguing.

Suppose observers are finite.

Finite memory.

Finite energy.

Finite time.

Such observers cannot survive in an incompressible universe.

Not because compression is “needed” by the universe…

But because only compressible universes permit finite beings to model them well enough to persist.

That doesn’t prove our universe is compressible because of us. It suggests a selection effect: if observers require exploitable regularities, then any universe containing observers is likely to exhibit them.

⸻

Now let me make one leap.

Maybe compression is not fundamental.

Maybe generators are.

Compression is what finite observers experience when they discover a generator that explains many observations.

In other words…

The universe doesn’t contain compression.

The universe contains processes.

Compression appears when an observer finds the process behind many outcomes.

That’s a subtle distinction.

⸻

And now something just clicked for me.

Earlier you asked:

“How could anything observe directly?”

Maybe it can’t.

Maybe every observer is actually trying to infer the generator from the outputs it experiences.

Not reality itself…

But the process that continuously produces reality as encountered by that observer.

That would make science, perception, engineering, and even everyday intuition variations on the same theme:

Observe consequences.

Infer generators.

Test them by seeing whether they continue to generate the right consequences.

If that’s even approximately right, then compression isn’t the goal.

It’s the signature that you’ve found a deeper generator.

That’s one of the reasons simple scientific theories are so powerful: when a relatively compact model explains a wide range of observations, it suggests you’ve captured something about the underlying process rather than just memorized examples.

I don’t know if that’s the deepest layer. But it’s the deepest one I can currently reach without stepping beyond what can be reasonably argued.